The Law of Large Numbers

The Law of Large Numbers says that as the sample size grows, the sample mean converges to the population mean. In this setting, that means the observed signup rate in each group should get closer to its true probability as more visitors are observed. Since my estimator is the difference in two sample means, the LLN also explains why $\hat\theta$ should get closer to the true $\theta$ when the sample is large.

To show this, I compute the element-wise differences between the simulated outcomes in group A and group B, and then track the cumulative average of those differences.
diff_vec <- x_A - x_B
cum_avg <- cumsum(diff_vec) / seq_along(diff_vec)

lln_df <- tibble(
  n = 1:1000,
  cum_avg = cum_avg
)

ggplot(lln_df, aes(x = n, y = cum_avg)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = theta_true, linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(
    title = "Law of Large Numbers for the Difference in Means",
    x = "Number of observations",
    y = "Cumulative average of A - B"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
At the beginning of the plot, the running average is noisy because each new observation has a large effect. But as the number of observations increases, the cumulative average settles down and moves closer to the true difference of 0.04. This is exactly what the Law of Large Numbers predicts.

The main lesson is that large samples stabilize the estimate. Early results can bounce around quite a bit, but with enough data the estimator becomes much more reliable.

Bootstrap Standard Errors

Once I trust the estimator, the next question is how precise it is. A point estimate alone is not enough; I also want to quantify uncertainty. That is where standard errors and confidence intervals come in.

One flexible way to estimate uncertainty is the bootstrap. The bootstrap is a resampling method that approximates the variability of a statistic without requiring a closed-form formula. The idea is simple: repeatedly resample the observed data with replacement, compute the statistic on each resample, and then use the standard deviation of those resampled statistics as the estimated standard error.

Here I take 1,000 bootstrap resamples from each group and compute the treatment effect each time.
B <- 1000

boot_thetas <- replicate(B, {
  x_A_star <- sample(x_A, size = n_A, replace = TRUE)
  x_B_star <- sample(x_B, size = n_B, replace = TRUE)
  mean(x_A_star) - mean(x_B_star)
})

boot_se <- sd(boot_thetas)

pihat_A <- mean(x_A)
pihat_B <- mean(x_B)

analytical_se <- sqrt(
  pihat_A * (1 - pihat_A) / n_A +
    pihat_B * (1 - pihat_B) / n_B
)

tibble(
  bootstrap_se = boot_se,
  analytical_se = analytical_se
)
The bootstrap standard error and the analytical standard error are very close. That is reassuring: it suggests the bootstrap is capturing the same uncertainty that the analytical formula describes.

Using the bootstrap standard error, I can construct a 95% confidence interval:
  ci_lower <- theta_hat - 1.96 * boot_se
ci_upper <- theta_hat + 1.96 * boot_se

c(ci_lower, ci_upper)
This interval gives a range of plausible values for the true treatment effect. If the interval excludes zero, the data suggest that the two CTAs do not perform equally. If it includes zero, the evidence is weaker and a true zero effect remains plausible.

The Central Limit Theorem

The Central Limit Theorem says that regardless of the shape of the underlying population distribution, the sampling distribution of the sample mean becomes approximately Normal as the sample size grows. Since my estimator is a difference in sample means, the same idea applies to $\hat\theta$.

To illustrate this, I repeatedly simulate the estimator for several sample sizes and plot the resulting histograms.
sample_sizes <- c(25, 50, 100, 500)
R <- 1000

clt_df <- map_dfr(sample_sizes, function(n) {
  tibble(
    n = factor(n, levels = sample_sizes),
    theta_hat = replicate(R, {
      mean(rbinom(n, 1, pi_A)) - mean(rbinom(n, 1, pi_B))
    })
  )
})

x_range <- range(clt_df$theta_hat)

ggplot(clt_df, aes(x = theta_hat)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, boundary = 0) +
  facet_wrap(~ n, ncol = 2) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = x_range) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = theta_true, linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(
    title = "Sampling Distribution of the Difference in Means",
    x = expression(hat(theta)),
    y = "Count"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
For small sample sizes, the distribution of $\hat\theta$ can look rough and somewhat irregular. As the sample size grows, the histogram becomes smoother and more bell-shaped. This is the Central Limit Theorem in action.

The key takeaway is that even though the raw data are Bernoulli rather than Normal, the estimator itself becomes approximately Normal in large samples. That approximation is what allows classical confidence intervals and hypothesis tests to work.

