Once I know the null distribution of the test statistic, I can compute a p-value.

This procedure is sometimes casually called a “t-test,” but that label is not exactly correct here. The classical t-test is derived under Normal data with an estimated variance, which leads to an exact t-distribution. In this setting the data are Bernoulli, not Normal, so there is no exact t-distribution result. What I am really using is a large-sample z-test justified by the CLT. In large samples, however, the t and Normal distributions are very similar, so the distinction is usually small in practice.
z_stat <- theta_hat / analytical_se
p_value <- 2 * (1 - pnorm(abs(z_stat)))

tibble(
  theta_hat = theta_hat,
  se = analytical_se,
  z_stat = z_stat,
  p_value = p_value
)
If the p-value is below 0.05, I would reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the data provide evidence of a difference between the two CTAs. If it is above 0.05, I would not reject the null. That does not prove the two CTAs are identical; it only means the evidence is not strong enough to rule out no difference.

The T-Test as a Regression

The two-sample test above is mathematically equivalent to a simple linear regression. This is useful because it shows that the same regression machinery used in many other settings can also handle A/B tests.

