The interpretation is simple. When $D_i = 0$, the expected value of $Y_i$ is $\beta_0$, which is the mean of group B and therefore estimates $\pi_B$. When $D_i = 1$, the expected value is $\beta_0 + \beta_1$, which is the mean of group A and therefore estimates $\pi_A$. It follows that $\beta_1 = \pi_A - \pi_B = \theta$, so the OLS estimate of $\beta_1$ is exactly the same quantity as the difference in sample means.
reg_df <- tibble(
  y = c(x_A, x_B),
  D = c(rep(1, n_A), rep(0, n_B))
)

reg_fit <- lm(y ~ D, data = reg_df)
tidy(reg_fit)
The coefficient on D should match the two-sample estimate $\hat\theta$. Its standard error, t-statistic, and p-value should also be very similar to what I computed earlier, aside from small differences due to how the standard error is estimated.

This equivalence matters because regression makes it easy to extend the analysis. Once the experiment is written as a regression, I can add controls, interactions, subgroup effects, or multiple treatment arms using the same framework.

The Problem with Peeking

Now consider a common temptation in practice. Instead of waiting until all 1,000 visitors per group have arrived, suppose I check the results every 100 visitors and stop the experiment as soon as one interim test is significant at the $\alpha = 0.05$ level.

This is problematic under classical frequentist statistics. A single test at the 5% level has a 5% chance of producing a false positive when the null is true. But if I repeatedly test the same experiment as data accumulate, each peek creates another opportunity for a false rejection. The overall probability of getting at least one false positive becomes much larger than 5%.

To show this, I simulate a world in which the null hypothesis is true: $\pi_A = \pi_B = 0.20$. I then run 10,000 simulated experiments. In each experiment, I peek after 100, 200, ..., 1000 observations per group and record whether any of the 10 tests is significant.
set.seed(54321)

pi0_A <- 0.20
pi0_B <- 0.20

one_peeking_experiment <- function() {
  xA <- rbinom(1000, 1, pi0_A)
  xB <- rbinom(1000, 1, pi0_B)

  peek_ns <- seq(100, 1000, by = 100)

  any(sapply(peek_ns, function(n) {
    pA <- mean(xA[1:n])
    pB <- mean(xB[1:n])

    se_n <- sqrt(
      pA * (1 - pA) / n +
      pB * (1 - pB) / n
    )

    z_n <- ifelse(se_n == 0, 0, (pA - pB) / se_n)
    pval_n <- 2 * (1 - pnorm(abs(z_n)))

    pval_n < 0.05
  }))
}

n_sims <- 10000
false_positive_rate <- mean(replicate(n_sims, one_peeking_experiment()))

false_positive_rate
A single test is supposed to have a false positive rate of 0.05 under the null. But once repeated peeking is allowed, the empirical false positive rate becomes substantially larger. That means I am more likely to declare a winner even when no true difference exists.

In practice, this is why repeated unadjusted peeking is dangerous in A/B testing. It inflates the Type I error rate and makes spurious results more likely. If interim monitoring is necessary, the stopping rule needs to be built into the design from the start using methods that properly account for repeated looks at the data.
